<h1>Density estimation II</h1>




<h3>Spline curves</h3>


<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Definition:</b>
A spline curve of order k is a piecewise polynomial of degree k
having continuous (k-1)-th derivatives. The junction points are called
<i>knots</i>. 
</td></tr></table>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   
   <table border=0>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   f(x)=
   </td>
   <td>
    x<sup>2</sup>
   </td>
   <td align=left>
    if x  &gt; 0
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
       
   </td>
   <td>
    0
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   else
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   </table>
   
   is a cubic spline, i.e., spline of degree 3. The only knot is 0.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Theorem:</b>
   Suppose that we are given k points
   
   <blockquote>
   (x<sub>1</sub>,y<sub>1</sub>),...,(x<sub>k</sub>,y<sub>k</sub>),
   </blockquote>
   
   where x<sub>1</sub>  &lt; ...  &lt; x<sub>k</sub>. Then among all
   square-integrable, twice-differentiable interpolants f(x) (with zero
   derivative at the two ends) the unique
   minimiser of 
   
   <blockquote>
   integral(f<sup>(2)</sup>(x))<sup>2</sup> dx
   </blockquote>
   
   is a cubic spline function. We call it <i>the</i> cubic spline interpolant
   for the given points.
   </td></tr></table>
   

To estimate density using cubic splines we first consider the empirical
distribution function: F<sub>n</sub>. It passes through
(X<sub>(i)</sub>,i/n). We find the cubic spline interpolant for these
points. Then we differentiate it to get the density estimator. 

<hr>

